## Introduction

The `@canva/app-middleware` package provides tools for building with Canva's Apps SDK. This SDK simplifies authentication for backend services that need to verify requests from Canva apps.

**Two ways to use this package:**

1. **Core function** (main export) - Works in any Node.js environment (Next.js, AWS Lambda, Cloudflare Workers, Fastify, Hono, etc.)
2. **Express middleware** (`/express`) - Ready-to-use middleware for Express.js applications

## Installation

```bash
npm install @canva/app-middleware
```

## Quick start

### Core function

Use the `initUserTokenVerifier` factory to create a verifier, then call `.verify()` per request:

```typescript
import { initUserTokenVerifier } from "@canva/app-middleware";

// Initialize once at app startup
const verifier = initUserTokenVerifier({
  appId: process.env.CANVA_APP_ID,
});

// Verify tokens per request
const payload = await verifier.verify(token);
console.log(payload.userId, payload.brandId);
```

#### Next.js API Route Example

```typescript
import {
  initUserTokenVerifier,
  TokenInvalidError,
} from "@canva/app-middleware";

// Initialize once at module level
const verifier = initUserTokenVerifier({
  appId: process.env.CANVA_APP_ID!,
});

export async function GET(request: Request) {
  const token = request.headers.get("Authorization")?.replace("Bearer ", "");

  if (!token) {
    return Response.json({ error: "Missing token" }, { status: 401 });
  }

  try {
    const payload = await verifier.verify(token);

    return Response.json({
      userId: payload.userId,
      brandId: payload.brandId,
    });
  } catch (error) {
    if (error instanceof TokenInvalidError) {
      return Response.json({ error: "Invalid token" }, { status: 401 });
    }
    throw error;
  }
}
```

#### AWS Lambda Example

```typescript
import { initUserTokenVerifier } from "@canva/app-middleware";

// Initialize once outside the handler (reused across invocations)
const verifier = initUserTokenVerifier({
  appId: process.env.CANVA_APP_ID,
});

export const handler = async (event) => {
  const token = event.headers.authorization?.replace("Bearer ", "");

  try {
    const payload = await verifier.verify(token);

    return {
      statusCode: 200,
      body: JSON.stringify({ userId: payload.userId }),
    };
  } catch (error) {
    return {
      statusCode: 401,
      body: JSON.stringify({ error: "Unauthorized" }),
    };
  }
};
```

### Express middleware

```typescript
import express from "express";
import { user } from "@canva/app-middleware/express";

const app = express();
const APP_ID = process.env.CANVA_APP_ID;

// Apply middleware to protected routes
app.use("/api", user.verifyToken({ appId: APP_ID }));

app.get("/api/user", (req, res) => {
  // Access the decoded JWT payload
  const { appId, userId, brandId } = req.canva.user;
  res.json({ appId, userId, brandId });
});

app.listen(3000);
```

## API

### Core Functions

#### initUserTokenVerifier()

Creates a verifier for Canva user JWT tokens. The verifier caches JWKS public keys according to the configured settings.

```typescript
import { initUserTokenVerifier } from "@canva/app-middleware";

const verifier = initUserTokenVerifier(options: UserTokenVerifierOptions): UserTokenVerifier;
```

##### Options

```typescript
type UserTokenVerifierOptions = {
  /** The ID of your Canva app (required) */
  appId: string;

  /** JWKS cache duration in minutes (default: 60) */
  cacheMaxAgeMinutes?: number;

  /** JWKS fetch timeout in milliseconds (default: 30000) */
  timeoutMs?: number;

  /** Base URL for JWKS endpoint (default: https://api.canva.com) */
  baseUrl?: string;
};
```

##### Return value

```typescript
type UserTokenVerifier = {
  /**
   * Verifies a Canva user JWT token and returns the decoded payload.
   * @param token - The JWT token to verify
   * @throws {TokenInvalidError} When the token is malformed or has an invalid signature
   * @throws {TokenExpiredError} When the token has expired
   */
  verify(token: string): Promise<UserTokenPayload>;
};

type UserTokenPayload = {
  appId: string; // The ID of the app
  userId: string; // The ID of the user
  brandId: string; // The ID of the user's team
};
```

### Express Middleware API

#### user.verifyToken()

Creates Express middleware for verifying Canva user JWT tokens obtained through [auth.getCanvaUserToken](https://www.canva.dev/docs/apps/api/latest/user-auth-get-canva-user-token/). By default, this middleware extracts the token from the `Authorization` header with a `Bearer` scheme.

```typescript
import { user } from "@canva/app-middleware/express";

user.verifyToken(options: UserAuthOptions): RequestHandler;
```

##### Options

```typescript
type UserAuthOptions = {
  /** The ID of your Canva app (required) */
  appId: string;

  /** Optional token extractor function */
  tokenExtractor?: TokenExtractor;

  /** JWKS cache duration in minutes (default: 60) */
  cacheMaxAgeMinutes?: number;

  /** JWKS fetch timeout in milliseconds (default: 30000) */
  timeoutMs?: number;

  /** Base URL for JWKS endpoint (default: https://api.canva.com) */
  baseUrl?: string;
};
```

| Parameter            | Type             | Description                                                                                                |
| -------------------- | ---------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| `appId`              | `string`         | **Required.** The ID of your Canva app from the [Developer Portal](https://www.canva.com/developers/apps). |
| `tokenExtractor`     | `TokenExtractor` | Optional. Function to extract tokens from requests. Defaults to `tokenExtractors.fromBearerAuth()`.        |
| `cacheMaxAgeMinutes` | `number`         | Optional. Duration to cache public keys (default: 60 minutes).                                             |
| `timeoutMs`          | `number`         | Optional. Timeout for fetching JWKS (default: 30 seconds).                                                 |
| `baseUrl`            | `string`         | Optional. Override the Canva API base URL (default: https://api.canva.com).                                |

##### Request augmentation

When a JWT is successfully verified, the middleware adds user context to the request:

```typescript
type Request = {
  canva: {
    user: {
      appId: string; // The ID of the app
      userId: string; // The ID of the user
      brandId: string; // The ID of the user's team
    };
  };
};
```

##### How it works

The middleware:

1. Extracts the JWT from the request using the provided token extractor
2. Decodes the JWT header to get the key ID (`kid`)
3. Fetches the public key from Canva's [JWKS endpoint](https://www.canva.dev/docs/apps/verifying-jwts/#step-4-get-the-active-public-key) (`https://api.canva.com/rest/v1/apps/{appId}/jwks`)
4. Verifies the JWT signature and validates the audience claim
5. Adds the decoded payload to `req.canva.user`

Public keys are cached for 60 minutes by default to improve performance and reduce load on the JWKS endpoint.

## Token extraction

The Express middleware provides built-in token extractors for common scenarios.

### From Authorization header (default)

By default, the middleware extracts the JWT from the `Authorization` header with a `Bearer` scheme:

```typescript
import { user } from "@canva/app-middleware/express";

app.use("/api", user.verifyToken({ appId: APP_ID }));
```

This expects requests with:

```
Authorization: Bearer <token>
```

### From query string

For scenarios where headers cannot be used (e.g., webhooks, redirects, or certain iframe contexts):

```typescript
import { user, tokenExtractors } from "@canva/app-middleware/express";

// Extract token from ?canva_user_token=<token>
app.use(
  "/webhook",
  user.verifyToken({
    appId: APP_ID,
    tokenExtractor: tokenExtractors.fromQuery("canva_user_token"),
  }),
);
```

### From cookies

Extract tokens from cookies (requires `cookie-parser` middleware):

```typescript
import cookieParser from "cookie-parser";
import { user, tokenExtractors } from "@canva/app-middleware/express";

app.use(cookieParser());
app.use(
  "/api",
  user.verifyToken({
    appId: APP_ID,
    tokenExtractor: tokenExtractors.fromCookie("canva_token"),
  }),
);
```

### Custom token extraction

You can provide a custom function to extract tokens from any location:

```typescript
import { user, type TokenExtractor } from "@canva/app-middleware/express";
import { TokenMissingError } from "@canva/app-middleware";

const customExtractor: TokenExtractor = (req) => {
  // Extract from custom header
  const token = req.header("X-Canva-Token");
  if (!token) {
    throw new TokenMissingError("Missing X-Canva-Token header");
  }
  return token;
};

app.use(
  "/api",
  user.verifyToken({
    appId: APP_ID,
    tokenExtractor: customExtractor,
  }),
);
```

## Error handling

The SDK uses a structured error hierarchy for precise error handling.

### Error types

All authentication errors extend `UserAuthError`:

```typescript
import {
  UserAuthError,
  TokenMissingError,
  TokenExpiredError,
  TokenInvalidError,
  AppIdMismatchError,
} from "@canva/app-middleware";
```

| Error Class          | Code              | Status Code | Description                               |
| -------------------- | ----------------- | ----------- | ----------------------------------------- |
| `TokenMissingError`  | `TOKEN_MISSING`   | 401         | JWT token not found in request            |
| `TokenExpiredError`  | `TOKEN_EXPIRED`   | 401         | Token has expired (includes `expiredAt`)  |
| `TokenInvalidError`  | `TOKEN_INVALID`   | 401         | Invalid signature or malformed token      |
| `AppIdMismatchError` | `APP_ID_MISMATCH` | 401         | Token `aud` doesn't match expected app ID |

All errors include a `statusCode` property that can be used directly when sending HTTP responses.

### Express error handling example

```typescript
import express from "express";
import { user } from "@canva/app-middleware/express";
import { UserAuthError, TokenExpiredError } from "@canva/app-middleware";

const app = express();

app.use("/api", user.verifyToken({ appId: process.env.CANVA_APP_ID }));

app.get("/api/user", (req, res) => {
  res.json(req.canva.user);
});

// Error handler must be defined after routes
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  if (err instanceof TokenExpiredError) {
    return res.status(err.statusCode).json({
      error: err.code,
      message: "Session expired",
    });
  }

  // Handle other UserAuthError instances
  if (err instanceof UserAuthError) {
    return res.status(err.statusCode).json({
      error: err.code,
      message: err.message,
    });
  }

  next(err);
});
```

### Best practices

- Always add error-handling middleware after your protected routes
- Use the structured error hierarchy to provide specific error messages
- Avoid exposing detailed error messages to clients in production
- Log errors for debugging and monitoring purposes

## Debugging

Enable debug logging by setting the `DEBUG` environment variable:

```bash
DEBUG=canva:app:middleware npm start
```

This logs information about JWT processing, including:

- Token extraction attempts
- Decoded payloads (after verification)
- Fallback extractor chains
- Any errors encountered

